%I A397065 #35 Jun 23 2026 09:39:38
%S A397065 1,1,2,4,11,28,86,273,915,3126,10948,38782,138719,499351,1808081,
%T A397065 6576500,24013937
%N A397065 Number of free polyominoes with n cells whose mirror curve consists of a single closed loop.
%C A397065 Draw the curve that runs diagonally at 45 degrees across the cells of a polyomino P, reflecting at the boundary edges and crossing over and under at interior points (the mirror curve of the polyomino, taking the boundary as the set of mirrors, with no internal mirrors). In general it decomposes into L(P) >= 1 disjoint closed loops; this sequence counts the n-cell shapes with L(P) = 1. These are the polyomino analog of the monolinear designs of the Chokwe sona (sand-drawing) tradition studied by Gerdes.
%C A397065 a(n) <= A000105(n), the number of free polyominoes with n cells, with equality for n <= 3.
%C A397065 For an m X n rectangle the mirror curve has exactly gcd(m,n) loops (see Gerdes), so such a rectangle is monolinear if and only if gcd(m,n) = 1. No general formula for the loop number of an arbitrary polyomino is known to the author; the problem of enumerating polyominoes by loop number was also raised informally by Yuan (2020).
%C A397065 Observation: the fraction a(n)/A000105(n) decreases steadily, from 1 at n = 3 to about 0.503 at n = 16, and may tend to 0.
%C A397065 Every tree-shaped polyomino (A131482) is monolinear, so A131482(n) <= a(n). The first strict inequality is a(6) = A131482(6) + 1 = 28, see the Example section and the Links section. - _Andrei Zabolotskii_, Jun 15 2026
%D A397065 P. Gerdes, Sona Geometry from Angola: Mathematics of an African Tradition, Polimetrica, Monza, 2006.
%D A397065 P. Gerdes, Lunda Geometry: Mirror Curves, Designs, Knots, Polyominoes, Patterns, Symmetries, Lulu, 2008.
%H A397065 S. Jablan, L. Radović, R. Sazdanović, and A. Zeković, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1106.3784">Mirror-curves and knot mosaics</a>, arXiv:1106.3784 [math.GT], 2011.
%H A397065 S. Jablan and L. Radović, <a href="https://doi.org/10.3390/sym4020302">Knots in art</a>, Symmetry, 4(2) (2012), 302-328.
%H A397065 William Montgomery, <a href="https://joaodascordas.com/oeis/a397065.html">Two kinds of loop: why a(6) = A131482(6) + 1</a>.
%H A397065 William Montgomery, <a href="/A397065/a397065.py.txt">Python program</a>
%H A397065 Matthew Yuan, <a href="https://medium.com/swlh/polyomino-loops-fc8f6fc92c2f">Polyomino loops</a>, Medium (The Startup), 2020.
%e A397065 For n = 4, of the 5 free tetrominoes only the 2 X 2 square has more than one loop (gcd(2,2) = 2); the I, L, T, and S tetrominoes each form a single loop, so a(4) = 4.
%e A397065 a(6) = 28: the 27 tree-shaped hexominoes (A131482(6) = 27) are all monolinear, and the only monolinear hexomino that is not tree-shaped is the 2 X 3 rectangle. Its mirror curve is a single loop (gcd(2,3) = 1), but its 2 X 2 subblocks put 4-cycles in the cell-adjacency graph, so it is not a tree.
%o A397065 (Python) # See William Montgomery link.
%Y A397065 Cf. A000105 (all free polyominoes, an upper bound), A131482 (tree-shaped polyominoes, a lower bound).
%K A397065 nonn,more,hard,new
%O A397065 1,3
%A A397065 _William Montgomery_, Jun 15 2026
